Historically, a [[grand jury|grand inquest]] impaneled and swore before the [[Justices in Eyre]], etc, endorsing a bill whereby any crime punishable in that court is presented to them, with the phrase '''billa vera''' ([[Latin language|Latin]]: "the bill is true"). This phrase signnifies that the presenter has furnished probable [[evidence]], and is worthy of further consideration, while the party presented is said to stand indicted of the crime, and must confess or follow through the indictment.

If the crime is punishable by death, it is further referred to another inquest, called the [[inquest of life and death]], by whom if he is found guilty, he stands convicted of the crime, and is condemned by the judge.

